  "diary": "Woke up early with actual energy today—rare for a Monday. The bus ride through the neighborhoods was gorgeous, everything green and golden in that early light. Had a solid morning with clients, then the whole office basically abandoned ship at 10 to catch the match at The Crocodile. USA-Wales was tense, and I got caught up in it more than I expected. There's something about watching a game with people you work alongside that makes it feel less lonely. Grabbed lunch at Matt's with everyone, still riding that post-game buzz. Afternoon was the usual grind—three back-to-back sessions, one kid really opening up about home stuff. Got home early enough to catch the tail end of the day. Spent the evening lost in the vinyl collection, spinning some old Coltrane, then tinkered with a new IPA recipe I've been wanting to try. Felt good to use my hands for something creative.",
  "thought_process": "The World Cup match was a gift, honestly. I needed the break from casework—not because I don't care, but because some days the weight of other people's problems sits heavy. Skipping the Light Rail closure didn't even affect me since I was already downtown anyway. The match gave me permission to be present with my colleagues as humans, not just coworkers. Afternoon felt lighter because of it. By evening, I was in my own head again, which is where I belong after a full day of listening. The vinyl and brewing are my reset buttons—they remind me I'm more than just the job.",
